One big memory
After more of 60 years of secrecy, the archives nazi of Bad Arolsen, which the fates the destiny of 17.5 millions of victims of the regime hitler, are in access free.
These 47 millions of documents from the archives, stored on 27 km of the board at Bad Arolsen In particular Hesse )- does not were far able to see that in an end « humanitarian », namely how individual and the spearhead, on request of a former victim or of its beneficiaries law.
These eleven Member States in charge of the management -dont the Germany, France, Israel and the Etats-Unis- have made of agreement in May 2006 for the open to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of the agreement by all countries is completed, the opening is effective since yesterday.
Information sensitive
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will of conduct research « particular on the movement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of workers forced », is Reto Meistern, the director of the archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross In particular the ICRC.
It recently, many countries, which Germany, are opposed to the opening to the public of these documents roll-call, the nature sensitive of some information.
For example the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some victims of the deportation.
The register of concentration camps or of warrants of arrest issued by the Gestapo had been gathered after war in an end practice: find the civilians deported or subject to the work force and, possibly, they provide a proof of their imprisonment, to open the way to their compensation.
Encore now at Bad Arolsen, most of 300 permanent deal of tens of thousands of requests individual.
Pourtant, for a part of the scientific community, the access to Bad Arolsen is a limited interest.
« It is there nothing of fundamentally new to wait of these documents », had said in 2006 the Pr Wolfgang Benz, director of the center for research on anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität of Berlin.
